<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Immunisation and anti-microbial drugs, particularly antibiotics, have made an enormous contribution to control of infectious disease and reduction of early death in the UK and throughout the world</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Joint written evidence submitted by the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">University of Southampton Medical School and the University College London Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust (AMR0024)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Prof George </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Lewith</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> University of Southampton Medical School </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Dr Peter Fisher Clinical Director, Royal London Hospital for Integrated Medicine, University College London Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust, Physician to The Queen. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">The government’s strategy</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Immunisation and anti-microbial agents, particularly antibiotics, have made an enormous contribution to control of infectious disease and reduction of early death in the UK and throughout the world.  However, as emphasised in the Chief Medical Officer’s Annual report, AMR is now a major problem.  Important contributory factors include inappropriate prescribing of antibiotics and their routine use in animal husbandry as growth promoters.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The government’s strategy on AMR focuses on: </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Better stewardship of antibiotics</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Development and deployment of improved diagnostic methods for infection</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Development of new antibiotics</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">While these are important, in our view the focus is too narrow.  This is essentially a convergent, ‘more of the same’ approach.  Unless there is a turnaround in the long-term downward trend in antibiotic discovery, this strategy will slow the spread of AMR, but not reverse it.   </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The evidence in the CMO’s report is largely hospital based with little reference to primary care and no mention of self-care.  Yet most inappropriate antibiotic prescribing occurs in primary care for self-limiting viral upper respiratory tract infections, despite numerous public health campaigns advising symptomatic measures such as rest, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">paracetamol</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and increased fluid intake rather than antibiotics for colds, coughs and sore throats. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">We advocate a more divergent approach incorporating, in addition to the measures proposed in the CMO’s Annual Report, research into other treatment options.  In particular, we believe that the potential of integrating traditional and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">traditioanl</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and complementary medicine methods, and the promotion of safe and appropriate self-care should be investigated.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">Primary care research projects on herbal medicine in infectious disease</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">A number of research projects with implications for AMR in, particularly around herbal treatment, are in progress at the National School for Primary Care Research.  These include:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">An NIHR funded study of the herb </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Uva</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ursi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> in acute urinary tract infection.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">An NIHR funded post-doctoral fellowship studying Chinese herbal remedies in recurrent urinary tract infections.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Projects submitted for funding, or in advanced development include:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Probiotics</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> (‘friendly’ bacteria) and Vitamin D in all cause infections in nursing home residents (MRC, EME board current submission).  </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">A clinical trial of the herb </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Pelargonium</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> for the treatment of lower respiratory tract infection.   This study is planned to be part commercial and part NIHR funded.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The clinical input in all these studies has involved collaboration between primary care departments within the NIHR National School for Primary Care Research.    The UCL School of Pharmacy has provided </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">phytopharmacy</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> input.  These projects reflect a sustained strategy designed to provide alternatives to antibiotics in primary care, led by departments of research excellence and high quality researchers including Prof Paul Little (Southampton University), </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Prof Chris Butler (Cardiff and Oxford University) and Prof Simon Gibbons (UCL School of Pharmacy)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">Promising herbal medicines</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Current evidence and systematic reviews suggest that herbs may have specific effects on acute infections and may also act synergistically with conventional medicines including antibiotics to diminish the risk of AMR. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">In the absence of effective antiviral orthodox therapy for self-limiting non-threatening viral infections, which are sometimes inappropriately treated with antibiotics or maybe complicated by bacterial </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">superinfection</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, a number of herbal extracts have potential.  These include: </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Andrographis</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">paniculata</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Pelargonium </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">sidoides</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> (a species of geranium), </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Echinacea species</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">garlic</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Sambucus</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">nigra</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> (elderberry), all of these are currently available in the UK as registered herbal medicines, and have shown promise in clinical trials for treatment or prevention of the common cold, acute bronchitis and sinusitis, and influenza. [2-7]</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The evidence suggests that they may act directly as antiviral agents and also stimulate boost immune system anti-viral activity. Replication of these results in independent, large, high quality clinical trials (such as is currently planned for </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Pelargonium</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">), combined with education of healthcare practitioners, community pharmacists, and the public, have the potential to enhance self-care, reduce GP attendances and antibiotic prescriptions, and allow patients to receive effective treatment for self-limiting viral illnesses.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The potential of herbs and plant extracts to potentiate antibiotics is a promising area for development, this includes some of the most dangerous antimicrobial resistant organisms.  At present most such work is preliminary and laboratory-based. But a recent review found evidence that 34 herbs may have such effects. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> For example resistant </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">E. coli</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> when combined with extracts of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Sophora</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">alopecuroides</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">became susceptible to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ciproﬂoxacin</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.  For MRSA </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Berberine</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, found in several medicinal plants, when combined the antibiotics </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">levofloxacin</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">azithromycin</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">(to which MRSA is resistant) restored their efficacy.[8-9]</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">That Several Chinese medicine plants have promising direct (</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ie</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> without being combined with antibiotics) anti-MRSA possibilities, these include </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Dendrobenthamia</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">capitata</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Elsholtzia</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">rugulosa</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Elsholtzia</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">blanda</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">, Geranium </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">strictipes</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Polygonum</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">multiflorum</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">  [10-11].</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">Homeopathy</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Homeopathy is controversial but is associated with reduced use of antibiotics in upper respiratory tract infections, an important source of inappropriate antibiotic prescribing in primary care.  This may be a result of the enhanced self-care that frequently occurs when patients seek and self-manage with CAM or it may be a specific effect. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">A Health Technology Assessment commissioned by the Swiss Federal government found 29 clinical trials of homeopathy for upper respiratory tract infection or allergies found 29 clinical studies of which 24 were positive for homeopathy.   When the 16 randomised placebo-controlled, trials only were analysed 8/16 were found to be statistically significantly positive, 4/16</span><span style="color:#2968b1; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">showed a positive trend.</span><span style="color:#2968b1; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Of trials comparing homeopathy with conventional treatment, 6/7 trials showed at least equivalence: 1/7 superior to conventional treatment, 5/7 equivalent to conventional treatment, one showed homeopathy to be inferior to conventional treatment (homeopathy v penicillin for streptococcal </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">pharyngitis</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> or tonsillitis).   The conclusion for homeopathy is ‘</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">probable effectiveness’. [12]</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">A study published since this Health Technology Assessment, supported by the Indian Ministry of Health involved collaboration between conventional ENT specialists and homeopathic doctors in a randomised controlled trial of homeopathy v conventional treatment in acute </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">otitis</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> media.  The outcomes at 3 weeks were not significantly different, but the numbers of antibiotic prescriptions in the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">homeopathically</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">-treated group were much lower. [13-14]</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Other evidence relevant to AMR includes preliminary clinical trial data suggesting that homeopathy may improve outcomes of critically-ill patients in intensive care units, and that it may be an effective treatment for E coli diarrhoea in newborn piglets. [15-16]</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">Developing self care </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Self-care is strongly associated with use of traditional and complementary medicine. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">There is huge potential to develop self-care with </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">traditional and complementary medicine </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">to manage the symptoms of acute infections and thus avoid patients requesting antibiotics.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Training community pharmacists in evidence based understanding of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">traditional and complementary </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">based approaches to self-care in acute self-limiting infections would increase their opportunist repertoire and allow patients who prefer such interventions more treatment options.  NHS Direct should provide appropriate guidance to the public.  In another domain (cancer), the website of Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Centre in New York City is an exemplar of public information on integrative medicine. [17]</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">Conclusions</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Traditional and complementary medicine methods have great potential for avoiding or averting the use of antibiotics, potentiating their effectiveness, and as novel antimicrobial agents.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">In addition, traditional and complementary medicine is strongly associated with self-care.  With appropriate promotion of their safe use and training of health care professionals, this can make a significant contribution to the reduction of inappropriate use of antimicrobial agents.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Considering its potential traditional and complementary medicine for AMR is greatly under researched.  Its potential should be taken into account in developing national AMR policy.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">References </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">1)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><a href="C:\Users\storeyj\AppData\Local\Microsoft\Windows\Temporary Internet Files\AppData\Local\Microsoft\Windows\Temporary Internet Files\Content.Outlook\0YR6E2GC\www.nhs.uk\NHSEngland\ARC\Pages\Whatareantibiotics.aspx"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">www.nhs.uk/NHSEngland/ARC/Pages/Whatareantibiotics.aspx</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">2)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Coon JT, Ernst E. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Andrographis</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">paniculata</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> in the treatment of upper respiratory tract infections: a sy